File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Variable all_dotsimp_denoms,  Next: Function check_overlaps n add_to_simps,  Up: affine

 -- Variable: all_dotsimp_denoms
     Default value: ‘false’

     When ‘all_dotsimp_denoms’ is a list, the denominators encountered
     by ‘dotsimp’ are appended to the list.  ‘all_dotsimp_denoms’ may be
     initialized to an empty list ‘[]’ before calling ‘dotsimp’.

     By default, denominators are not collected by ‘dotsimp’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function check_overlaps n add_to_simps,  Next: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Prev: Variable all_dotsimp_denoms,  Up: affine

 -- Function: check_overlaps (N, ADD_TO_SIMPS)
     Checks the overlaps thru degree _n_, making sure that you have
     sufficient simplification rules in each degree, for ‘dotsimp’ to
     work correctly.  This process can be speeded up if you know before
     hand what the dimension of the space of monomials is.  If it is of
     finite global dimension, then ‘hilbert’ should be used.  If you
     don't know the monomial dimensions, do not specify a
     ‘rank_function’.  An optional third argument ‘reset’, ‘false’ says
     don't bother to query about resetting things.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Next: Function dotsimp f,  Prev: Function check_overlaps n add_to_simps,  Up: affine

 -- Function: declare_weights (X_1, W_1, ..., X_N, W_N)
     Assigns weights _w_1_, ..., _w_n_ to _x_1_, ..., _x_n_,
     respectively.  These are the weights used in computing ‘nc_degree’.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function dotsimp f,  Next: Function extract_linear_equations p_1 ... p_n m_1 ... m_n,  Prev: Function declare_weights x_1 w_1 ... x_n w_n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: dotsimp (F)
     Returns 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal generated by the
     equations, i.e., if and only if _f_ is a polynomial combination of
     the elements of the equations.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function extract_linear_equations p_1 ... p_n m_1 ... m_n,  Next: Function fast_central_elements x_1 ... x_n n,  Prev: Function dotsimp f,  Up: affine

 -- Function: extract_linear_equations (P_1, ..., P_N, M_1, ..., M_N)
     Makes a list of the coefficients of the noncommutative polynomials
     _p_1_, ..., _p_n_ of the noncommutative monomials _m_1_, ...,
     _m_n_.  The coefficients should be scalars.  Use
     ‘list_nc_monomials’ to build the list of monomials.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function fast_central_elements x_1 ... x_n n,  Next: Function fast_linsolve expr_1 ... expr_m x_1 ... x_n,  Prev: Function extract_linear_equations p_1 ... p_n m_1 ... m_n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: fast_central_elements (X_1, ..., X_N, N)
     If ‘set_up_dot_simplifications’ has been previously done, finds the
     central polynomials in the variables _x_1_, ..., _x_n_ in the given
     degree, _n_.

     For example:

     set_up_dot_simplifications ([y.x + x.y], 3);
     fast_central_elements ([x, y], 2);
     [y.y, x.x];

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function fast_linsolve expr_1 ... expr_m x_1 ... x_n,  Next: Function grobner_basis expr_1 ... expr_m,  Prev: Function fast_central_elements x_1 ... x_n n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: fast_linsolve (EXPR_1, ..., EXPR_M, X_1, ..., X_N)
     Solves the simultaneous linear equations _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_
     for the variables _x_1_, ..., _x_n_.  Each _expr_i_ may be an
     equation or a general expression; if given as a general expression,
     it is treated as an equation of the form ‘expr_i = 0’.

     The return value is a list of equations of the form ‘[x_1 = a_1,
     ..., x_n = a_n]’ where _a_1_, ..., _a_n_ are all free of _x_1_,
     ..., _x_n_.

     ‘fast_linsolve’ is faster than ‘linsolve’ for system of equations
     which are sparse.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function grobner_basis expr_1 ... expr_m,  Next: Function list_nc_monomials list_nc_monomials p_1 ... p_n list_nc_monomials p,  Prev: Function fast_linsolve expr_1 ... expr_m x_1 ... x_n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: grobner_basis (EXPR_1, ..., EXPR_M)
     Returns a Groebner basis for the equations _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_.
     The function ‘polysimp’ can then be used to simplify other
     functions relative to the equations.

     grobner_basis ([3*x^2+1, y*x])$
     
     polysimp (y^2*x + x^3*9 + 2) ==> -3*x + 2

     ‘polysimp(f)’ yields 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal generated
     by _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_, that is, if and only if _f_ is a
     polynomial combination of the elements of _expr_1_, ..., _expr_m_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function list_nc_monomials list_nc_monomials p_1 ... p_n list_nc_monomials p,  Next: Function mono x_1 ... x_n n,  Prev: Function grobner_basis expr_1 ... expr_m,  Up: affine

 -- Function: list_nc_monomials (LIST_NC_MONOMIALS, P_1, ..., P_N,
          LIST_NC_MONOMIALS, P)
     Returns a list of the non commutative monomials occurring in a
     polynomial _p_ or a list of polynomials _p_1_, ..., _p_n_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function mono x_1 ... x_n n,  Next: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Prev: Function list_nc_monomials list_nc_monomials p_1 ... p_n list_nc_monomials p,  Up: affine

 -- Function: mono (X_1, ..., X_N, N)
     Returns the list of independent monomials relative to the current
     dot simplifications of degree _n_ in the variables _x_1_, ...,
     _x_n_.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Next: Function nc_degree p,  Prev: Function mono x_1 ... x_n n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: monomial_dimensions (N)
     Compute the Hilbert series through degree _n_ for the current
     algebra.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function nc_degree p,  Next: Function set_up_dot_simplifications set_up_dot_simplifications eqns check_through_degree set_up_dot_simplifications eqns,  Prev: Function monomial_dimensions n,  Up: affine

 -- Function: nc_degree (P)
     Returns the degree of a noncommutative polynomial _p_.  See
     ‘declare_weights’.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function set_up_dot_simplifications set_up_dot_simplifications eqns check_through_degree set_up_dot_simplifications eqns,  Prev: Function nc_degree p,  Up: affine

 -- Function: set_up_dot_simplifications (SET_UP_DOT_SIMPLIFICATIONS,
          EQNS, CHECK_THROUGH_DEGREE, SET_UP_DOT_SIMPLIFICATIONS, EQNS)
     The _eqns_ are polynomial equations in non commutative variables.
     The value of ‘current_variables’ is the list of variables used for
     computing degrees.  The equations must be homogeneous, in order for
     the procedure to terminate.

     If you have checked overlapping simplifications in
     ‘dot_simplifications’ above the degree of _f_, then the following
     is true: ‘dotsimp (f)’ yields 0 if and only if _f_ is in the ideal
     generated by the equations, i.e., if and only if _f_ is a
     polynomial combination of the elements of the equations.

     The degree is that returned by ‘nc_degree’.  This in turn is
     influenced by the weights of individual variables.

     ‘load("affine")’ loads this function.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: atensor,  Next: cartan,  Prev: affine,  Up: Maxima Core Documentation

1.124 atensor
=============

* Menu:

* Function abasep v::
* Variable adim::
* Function af u v::
* Variable aform::
* Function alg_type ::
* Variable asymbol::
* Function atensimp expr::
* Function av u v::
* Function init_atensor init_atensor alg_type opt_dims init_atensor alg_type::
* Function sf u v::


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function abasep v,  Next: Variable adim,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: abasep (V)
     Checks if its argument is an ‘atensor’ base vector.  That is, if it
     is an indexed symbol, with the symbol being the same as the value
     of ‘asymbol’, and the index having a numeric value between 1 and
     ‘adim’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Variable adim,  Next: Function af u v,  Prev: Function abasep v,  Up: atensor

 -- Variable: adim
     Default value: 0

     The dimensionality of the algebra.  ‘atensor’ uses the value of
     ‘adim’ to determine if an indexed object is a valid base vector.
     See ‘abasep’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function af u v,  Next: Variable aform,  Prev: Variable adim,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: af (U, V)
     An antisymmetric scalar function that is used in commutation
     relations.  The default implementation checks if both arguments are
     base vectors using ‘abasep’ and if that is the case, substitutes
     the corresponding value from the matrix ‘aform’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Variable aform,  Next: Function alg_type,  Prev: Function af u v,  Up: atensor

 -- Variable: aform
     Default value: ‘ident(3)’

     Default values for the bilinear forms ‘sf’, ‘af’, and ‘av’.  The
     default is the identity matrix ‘ident(3)’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function alg_type,  Next: Variable asymbol,  Prev: Variable aform,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: alg_type ()
     The algebra type.  Valid values are ‘universal’, ‘grassmann’,
     ‘clifford’, ‘symmetric’, ‘symplectic’ and ‘lie_envelop’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Variable asymbol,  Next: Function atensimp expr,  Prev: Function alg_type,  Up: atensor

 -- Variable: asymbol
     Default value: ‘v’

     The symbol for base vectors.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function atensimp expr,  Next: Function av u v,  Prev: Variable asymbol,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: atensimp (EXPR)
     Simplifies an algebraic tensor expression _expr_ according to the
     rules configured by a call to ‘init_atensor’.  Simplification
     includes recursive application of commutation relations and
     resolving calls to ‘sf’, ‘af’, and ‘av’ where applicable.  A
     safeguard is used to ensure that the function always terminates,
     even for complex expressions.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function av u v,  Next: Function init_atensor init_atensor alg_type opt_dims init_atensor alg_type,  Prev: Function atensimp expr,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: av (U, V)
     An antisymmetric function that is used in commutation relations.
     The default implementation checks if both arguments are base
     vectors using ‘abasep’ and if that is the case, substitutes the
     corresponding value from the matrix ‘aform’.

     For instance:

     (%i1) load("atensor");
     (%o1)       /share/tensor/atensor.mac
     (%i2) adim:3;
     (%o2)                                  3
     (%i3) aform:matrix([0,3,-2],[-3,0,1],[2,-1,0]);
                                    [  0    3   - 2 ]
                                    [               ]
     (%o3)                          [ - 3   0    1  ]
                                    [               ]
                                    [  2   - 1   0  ]
     (%i4) asymbol:x;
     (%o4)                                  x
     (%i5) av(x[1],x[2]);
     (%o5)                                 x
                                            3


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function init_atensor init_atensor alg_type opt_dims init_atensor alg_type,  Next: Function sf u v,  Prev: Function av u v,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: init_atensor (INIT_ATENSOR, ALG_TYPE, OPT_DIMS,
          INIT_ATENSOR, ALG_TYPE)
     Initializes the ‘atensor’ package with the specified algebra type.
     _alg_type_ can be one of the following:

     ‘universal’: The universal algebra has no commutation rules.

     ‘grassmann’: The Grassman algebra is defined by the commutation
     relation ‘u.v+v.u=0’.

     ‘clifford’: The Clifford algebra is defined by the commutation
     relation ‘u.v+v.u=-2*sf(u,v)’ where ‘sf’ is a symmetric
     scalar-valued function.  For this algebra, _opt_dims_ can be up to
     three nonnegative integers, representing the number of positive,
     degenerate, and negative dimensions of the algebra, respectively.
     If any _opt_dims_ values are supplied, ‘atensor’ will configure the
     values of ‘adim’ and ‘aform’ appropriately.  Otherwise, ‘adim’ will
     default to 0 and ‘aform’ will not be defined.

     ‘symmetric’: The symmetric algebra is defined by the commutation
     relation ‘u.v-v.u=0’.

     ‘symplectic’: The symplectic algebra is defined by the commutation
     relation ‘u.v-v.u=2*af(u,v)’ where ‘af’ is an antisymmetric
     scalar-valued function.  For the symplectic algebra, _opt_dims_ can
     be up to two nonnegative integers, representing the nondegenerate
     and degenerate dimensions, respectively.  If any _opt_dims_ values
     are supplied, ‘atensor’ will configure the values of ‘adim’ and
     ‘aform’ appropriately.  Otherwise, ‘adim’ will default to 0 and
     ‘aform’ will not be defined.

     ‘lie_envelop’: The algebra of the Lie envelope is defined by the
     commutation relation ‘u.v-v.u=2*av(u,v)’ where ‘av’ is an
     antisymmetric function.

     The ‘init_atensor’ function also recognizes several predefined
     algebra types:

     ‘complex’ implements the algebra of complex numbers as the Clifford
     algebra Cl(0,1).  The call ‘init_atensor(complex)’ is equivalent to
     ‘init_atensor(clifford,0,0,1)’.

     ‘quaternion’ implements the algebra of quaternions.  The call
     ‘init_atensor (quaternion)’ is equivalent to ‘init_atensor
     (clifford,0,0,2)’.

     ‘pauli’ implements the algebra of Pauli-spinors as the
     Clifford-algebra Cl(3,0).  A call to ‘init_atensor(pauli)’ is
     equivalent to ‘init_atensor(clifford,3)’.

     ‘dirac’ implements the algebra of Dirac-spinors as the
     Clifford-algebra Cl(3,1).  A call to ‘init_atensor(dirac)’ is
     equivalent to ‘init_atensor(clifford,3,0,1)’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function sf u v,  Prev: Function init_atensor init_atensor alg_type opt_dims init_atensor alg_type,  Up: atensor

 -- Function: sf (U, V)
     A symmetric scalar function that is used in commutation relations.
     The default implementation checks if both arguments are base
     vectors using ‘abasep’ and if that is the case, substitutes the
     corresponding value from the matrix ‘aform’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: cartan,  Next: ctensor,  Prev: atensor,  Up: Maxima Core Documentation

1.125 cartan
============

* Menu:

* Function ext_diff form::
* Function init_cartan x_1 ... x_m::
* Function lie_diff vector1 vector2 form::
* Function | ::
* Function ~ ::


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function ext_diff form,  Next: Function init_cartan x_1 ... x_m,  Up: cartan

 -- Function: ext_diff (FORM)
     The exterior derivative operator.  It takes one argument, which
     should be a differential form.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function init_cartan x_1 ... x_m,  Next: Function lie_diff vector1 vector2 form,  Prev: Function ext_diff form,  Up: cartan

 -- Function: init_cartan (X_1, ..., X_M)
     Initializes some global variables for the package.  The argument, a
     Maxima list, is an ordered list of coordinates.  The coordinate
     list is stored as the value of the variable ‘cartan_coords’.  The
     value of the variable ‘cartan_basis’ is a list of the basis
     1-forms.  The dimension is stored as the value of the variable
     ‘cartan_dim’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function lie_diff vector1 vector2 form,  Next: Function |,  Prev: Function init_cartan x_1 ... x_m,  Up: cartan

 -- Function: lie_diff (VECTOR1, VECTOR2, FORM)
     The Lie derivative operator.  The first argument is a vector field.
     The second argument may be either a vector field or a differential
     form.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function |,  Next: Function ~,  Prev: Function lie_diff vector1 vector2 form,  Up: cartan

 -- Function: | ()
     The bar "|" is an infix operator which defines the contraction of a
     vector on a form.  The vector should be given on the left.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: Function ~,  Prev: Function |,  Up: cartan

 -- Function: ~ ()
     The tilde "~" is an infix operator which denotes the exterior
     (wedge) product.  The canonical ordering of the products is
     determined by the order in which the coordinates were specified.
     For example, if the coordinate list is specified as ‘[x,y,z]’, then
     the two-form ‘dy~dx’ simplifies to ‘-dx~dy’.


File: maxima-core-docs.info,  Node: ctensor,  Next: itensor,  Prev: cartan,  Up: Maxima Core Documentation

